The baseline model performed reasonably well but showed clear signs of overfitting. 
Training accuracy continued to increase steadily, while validation accuracy plateaued early and validation loss began to rise. 
This indicates that the model was starting to memorize the training data rather than generalize to new data.

The improved model incorporated multiple overfitting mitigation techniques, including L2 regularization, dropout, batch normalization, data augmentation, and early stopping. 
These changes significantly improved generalization. Validation accuracy increased, validation loss decreased, and the gap between training and validation curves became much smaller, which can also be observed in the training/validation accuracy and loss plots.

Among these techniques, data augmentation had the largest impact because it effectively increased the size and diversity of the training dataset. 
By introducing transformations such as rotation and flipping, the model was exposed to more varied examples, improving its ability to generalize. 
Dropout reduces co-adaptation by forcing neurons to learn more robust features. L2 regularization helped control model complexity by penalizing large weights. 
Batch normalization stabilized training and improved convergence speed. Early stopping prevented the model from overfitting during later epochs by halting training once validation performance stopped improving.

Overall, the improved model achieved higher test accuracy and demonstrated significantly better generalization compared to the baseline model.
